'''Lance Brooks''' (born January 1, 1984) is an [[United States|American]] [[discus throw]]er who has qualified to compete in the [[2012 Summer Olympics]].  He graduated from [[Millikin University]] in 2006.  In 2009, he finished fourth in the discus at the US Outdoor Championships.  In 2011, he finished third at the same event, qualifying for the World Championships, where he finished 13th. At the 2012 Olympic Trails, he placed first with a new personal best of {{convert|65.15|m}}. In so doing, he achieved the Olympic "A" Standard for the first time of his career.

==Early life==
Lance Brooks was born January 1, 1984 in [[New Berlin, Illinois]].<ref name=bio>{{cite web|title=USA Track & Field: Lance Brooks|url=http://www.usatf.org/Athlete-Bios/Lance-Brooks.aspx|accessdate=July 1, 2012}}</ref>  At birth, he weighed {{convert|10|lb}} and was {{convert|22.25|in}} long, making him an exceptionally large baby.<ref name=official>{{cite web|title=Lane's Biography|url=http://lancebrooksolympics.com/bio.php|accessdate=July 1, 2012}}</ref> His first participated in competitive sports during fourth grade, playing basketball at the [[YMCA]].<ref name=official />  At the time, the school didn't have a [[track and field]] team.  In eighth grade, his parents successfully petitioned the school board to allow Brooks to be a one-person team.<ref name=official />   The next year, 50 students joined the team.<ref name=official />

Brooks attended [[New Berlin High School]], where he played [[baseball]] and basketball.<ref name=bio />   He participated in several track and field events, excelling at discuss.  He won the event at almost every meet and was the state discuss champion his senior year.<ref name=official />  Throughout his school years, Brooks was very active in [[Boy Scouts of American|Boy Scouts]], achieving the rank of [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]].<ref name=bio /><ref name=official />

After graduation, Brooks attended [[Millikin University]], earning a [[Bachelor of Science]] in [[Environmental Science] in 2006.<ref name=official />  During college, he played [[basketball]] and did [[track and field]].<ref name=lifting>{{cite news|title=Discus hopeful Brooks does the heavy lifting|author=Helene Elliott|date=June 25, 2012|work=Chicago Tribune|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-06-25/sports/ct-spt-0626-olympics-track--20120626_1_discus-millikin-olympic|accessdate=July 1, 2012}}</ref><ref name=bio />  He set a school record in discus (57.83m/189ft 9in) but did not consider seriously competing in the sport.<ref name=bio /><ref name=qualifies />  Brooks a NCAA Division III [[All-American]] during his stay at Millikin.<ref name=bio />

==Athletic career==
After college, Brooks moved to [[Boulder, Colorado]] to train and teach track and field at the high school level.<ref name=bio />  The went to graduate school at [[University of Colorado]] for one semester.<ref name=official />  He qualified for the [[2008 United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|2008 Olympic Trials]], but did not make the team.<ref name=official />

In 2009, Brooks finished fourth in discus at the [[2009 USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships|US Outdoor Championships]], narrowly missing qualifying for World's.  In 2010, he set a new personal best, throwing 64.79 meters, and finished the year ranked number 24 in the world.<ref name=bio /> At the 2011, National Outdoor Championships, Brooks placed third in the discus with a score of {{convert|63.45|m}}.<ref name=bio />  The score, which he achieve on his final throw, was good enough to qualify him for [[2011 World Championships in Athletics|2011 World Championships]].<ref name=qualifies />  At the World's, he finished 13th.<ref name=bio />  For the year, he was ranked number 38 in the world at the discus.<ref name=bio />

At the [[2012 United States Olympic Trials (track and field)|2012 Olympic Trials]], led all six rounds of the competition throwing over {{convert|64|m}} of each of his first three throws.<ref name=qualifies>{{cite news|title=Lance Brooks, Denver discus thrower, qualifies for Olympics on final effort|work=Denver Post|date=June 29, 2012|author=John Meyer|url=http://www.denverpost.com/olympics/ci_20968694/ex-cu-runner-jenny-simpsons-mind-wildfires-during|accessdate=Jule 1, 2012}}</ref>  However, he had not met the "A" Standard required to make the Olympic team in any previous event, and thus was in danger of winning the event but failing to [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Qualification|qualify for the Olympics]].  On his final throw, he achieved a distance of {{convert|65.15|m}}, winning the event with a new personal best and meeting the required standard of 65 meters.<ref name=qualifies /> On his last throw, Brooks remarked: "I knew I had to calm down on my last throw. I just kind of took a minute and relaxed and tried not to tense up because that's what ruined my fourth and fifth throws [on which he fouled]. I knew I could throw it, it was just a matter of getting through it."<ref name=qualifies />  The entire competition was held in the rain, inhibiting the competitor's throwing ability.<ref name=qualifies />

Brooks is coached by Steve DeAutremont and sponsored by [[Nike]].<ref name=bio />

==Personal life==
Brooks currently lives in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]] where he is employed as a throwing coach (shot put and discuss) at teh high school level. <ref name=official />  He also works for an oil and gas company and in construction.<ref name=official />  "It's probably not the ideal job to have as an athlete," he told a reporter,  "but it pays the bills and you've got to do what you've got to do."<ref name=lifting />

